post_text:
An arrival update for NRES families for Tuesday and Thursday this week!
For Tuesday, August 25th (Group #1 A-K) and Thursday, August 26th (Group #2 L-Z) parents will be asked to drop their students off in the back of the building off of Ridgewood Road West.

The lot will be closed to cars for our morning gathering. Please only drop students off in the back. Parents may drop their student(s) off along the curb and have them walk to the lot where there will be staff to direct them to their grade level area. We will have numbered balloons to also indicate grade level locations. Parents are welcome to walk their student(s) up to the lot. We just ask that you activate your superpowers by masking‚Ä¶

post_text:
This year more than ever, it's up to all of us to keep our schools healthy and safe for students and staff!
One of the best ways you can help is by keeping your students (or yourself!) home during illnesses. Help us spread the word about the importance of staying home when experiencing symptoms to protect our students, staff, families, and community by adding this frame to your profile and pledging to stay home when you're sick!
Make sure you save our downloadable daily health assessment for quick reference each day at https://bit.ly/2CRgQib.
Use the Try It button below to add to your profile! If you don't see the Try It button, search for NELSD Pledge at https://www.facebook.com/profilepicframes or click on your profile photo on your page and select "Add a Frame."
#NELSDpride

post_text:
NELSD will operate on a hybrid model for the first four weeks of the school year. In the hybrid model, schools operate at a reduced capacity (50 percent) with safety precautions in place.

The decision to begin the year on the hybrid schedule was made for staff to work with smaller groups to ensure students understand the new safety procedures in place and to help prepare them for any necessary periods of online learning by sharing the tools teachers will use during remote learning.

Online learning students will continue to learn at home each school day.

Visit our website for more details: https://bit.ly/33XIfKo.

post_text:
After careful consideration and discussions with the Clark County Combined Health District, the Class of 2020 Graduation ceremonies for Northeastern High School and Kenton Ridge High School on June 29-30 have been cancelled.
While we tried to allow as much time as possible for conditions to improve with the hope that we would be able to have our traditional ceremony, it is clear that a large gathering will not be possible next week.
We are grateful to all of our students and families who joined us to celebrate their individual graduations in May. In lieu of the traditional graduation ceremonies, we will celebrate the achievements of the Class of 2020 by releasing the compiled videos of‚Ä¶ More

Share this with families who have children ages 4-6!
This Friday, Clark County Sheriff's Deputies Josh Berner and Shaun Lisle will be distributing free Safety Village materials (show in the picture below) to children ages 4-6 years old, in lieu of the annual Safety Village offered by the Clark County Sheriff's Office - Ohio.
Deputy Berner and Deputy Lisle will be in the parking lot of Northridge School from 8-9 a.m. and 1-2 p.m. on Friday, June 26. Thank you, Deputy Berner and Deputy Lisle, for going above and beyond to help spread good safety practices to kids in Clark County!

post_text:
Graduation Update

At NELSD, our staff is committed to celebrating the accomplishments of our Class of 2020 Seniors. Recognizing that these students have sacrificed many of the traditional memories that make up the senior year, we have created a plan that will provide recognition and opportunities for celebration for students and their families.
From May 18 through May 29, all seniors will be given an appointment time to report to their school with up to six (6) family members. While wearing his/her cap and gown, each student will walk across the stage, be presented his or her diploma, and have a photo taken with family to be used at our graduation ceremony. Students and their families will‚Ä¶ More

post_text:
South Vienna Middle School Student Council members picked up trash around the South Vienna community while practicing social distancing on Saturday morning.
The service project was suggested by the Student Council President, Violet Bonham, after noticing large amounts of trash on the sides of roads. Students and families collected over 20 bags of trash from around the community! Thank you to all the community members who showed appreciation and even stopped to thank families for their efforts! #NELSDpride

post_text:
The NELSD Facilities Project Groundbreaking, originally scheduled for May 15, has been postponed to the fall of 2020, due to Ohio Governor Mike DeWine‚Äôs April 20 announcement that school buildings will be closed for the remainder of the 2019-2020 school year.
This does not impact the work schedule for the project, but makes sure that our students, staff, and community will have the opportunity to be part of the groundbreaking.
A new groundbreaking date will be shared with the community as we get a clearer picture from the state about large gathering guidelines for the fall.
Stay tuned for a district update about progress on the facilities project on Wednesday, April 29, 2020.
More at http://ow.ly/SDnV50zlacz.

We are grateful for our supportive community and have heard from many who would like to help with feeding students and families during the school closure. We are waiting for guidance from the state about our options as a district, but wanted to share that our partners at Second Harvest Food Bank of Clark, Champaign & Logan Counties are developing a plan of packing boxes that will be delivered to sites throughout the community for pick-up.
If you'd like to help, you can make a donation to the Second Harvest Food Bank or contact Tyra Jackson at tjackson@theshfb.org for more information on how to get involved!

post_text: Last week, Mr. Rethman's 5th grade Science students at Rolling Hills learned about Mars from a special guest! Ron Stauffer, a presenter from Wright Patterson Air Force Base Educational Outreach Office, visited to present about the land features of Mars, our missions and future explorations to Mars, and why Mars has the potential to have life on the planet in the future. He showed the students the types of rocks that would be there and even used 3D imagery and 3D glasses for students to show them how the land on Mars would look. Thank you, Mr. Stauffer! #NELSDpride

post_text: Congratulations to Caitlin Haack of NEHS who was honored as one of the Exchange Club of Springfield, Ohio Students of the Month! #NELSDpride
shared_text:
Exchange Club of Springfield, Ohio
January 19 at 10:05 PM ¬∑

Tuesday January 14, 2020, the Exchange Club of Springfield welcomed the first four of twelve high school Students of the Month.

Those proudly representing their schools were, from Global Impact STEM Academy, Isaiah Stickley, from Greenon, Makenna Young, from Northeastern, Caitlin Haack, and from Northwestern, Hannah Swenson. All Exchangites who attended were amazed at the extent of their involvement with the community and school activities!

The students each received a stipend of $100 as Youth of the Month, and have promised to participate in the essay contest and the chance to earn Youth of the Year honors and the $1,000 scholarship for First place. Additional scholarships are in the amount of $500 for Second, and $250 for placing Third, and will also be awarded at the annual Youth of the Year Banquet on March 24, 2020 at the Wittenberg University Benham-Pence Student Center.

We are also hoping for an A.C.E. Award candidate, who will also receive a $ 1,000 college scholarship. Great job Teresa Metzger and Peg Haemmerle YoY Committee!
